      <hedline>
        <hl1>An Olympic Moment</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Matthew B Dwyer letter says Rulon Gardner's win in Greco-Roman wrestling at Sydney Olympics was one of greatest upsets in history of any sport</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rulon Gardner's defeat of Aleksandr Karelin in Greco-Roman wrestling was not only ''one of the most  startling upsets in Olympic wrestling history,'' but also one of the greatest upsets in the history of any sport (''Even 286-Pound Legends Lose Eventually,'' Sports pages, Sept. 28).</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Rulon Gardner's defeat of Aleksandr Karelin in Greco-Roman wrestling was not only ''one of the most  startling upsets in Olympic wrestling history,'' but also one of the greatest upsets in the history of any sport (''Even 286-Pound Legends Lose Eventually,'' Sports pages, Sept. 28).</p>
        <p>Gardner's overtime defeat of Karelin is the Olympic moment we have been waiting for. Watching this unknown underdog defy every expectation is far more exciting than watching a hundred Michael Johnsons or Marion Joneses simply meeting everyone's expectations.</p>
        <p>MATTHEW B. DWYER  New York, Sept. 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
